Task #6 (Login/Logout) is next. Here are the design specs:

## Login Page Design

Same narrow centered form layout as registration:

```html
<div class="auth-form">
  <h1>Sign in</h1>
  <!-- Error banner (only on failed login, generic message) -->
  <div class="auth-form__message auth-form__message--error" role="alert">
    That email or password didn't work. Try again.
  </div>
  <form method="post" action="/login" class="auth-form__fields">
    <div class="auth-form__group">
      <label for="email">Email</label>
      <input type="email" id="email" name="email" autocomplete="email" required>
    </div>
    <div class="auth-form__group">
      <label for="password">Password</label>
      <input type="password" id="password" name="password" autocomplete="current-password" required>
    </div>
    <button type="submit" class="auth-form__submit">Sign in</button>
  </form>
  <p class="auth-form__footer">
    Don't have an account? <a href="/register">Create one</a>
  </p>
</div>
```

Key differences from registration:
- **No field-level validation errors** -- login failures show only the generic banner ("That email or password didn't work. Try again."). Never reveal which field is wrong.
- **`autocomplete="current-password"`** not `new-password`
- **Submit button**: "Sign in" (not "Create account")
- **Footer link**: Points to registration instead of login
- **Forgot password link**: Per US-2, add a "Forgot password?" link below the form. For MVP it leads to a placeholder page. Put it in the footer area: `<p class="auth-form__footer">Forgot password? <a href="/forgot-password">Reset it</a></p>` -- or combine with the register link in the same footer block.

The existing `.auth-form` CSS handles all of this. No new component CSS needed.

## Authenticated Page Header (for logout)

When a user is logged in, pages need a header with logout:

```html
<header>
  <nav class="container site-header" aria-label="Main navigation">
    <a href="/" class="site-header__brand">Todo List</a>
    <div class="site-header__actions">
      <span>{{ user_email }}</span>
      <form method="post" action="/logout">
        <button type="submit" class="button--text">Sign out</button>
      </form>
    </div>
  </nav>
</header>
```

This needs new CSS. Add to the components layer:

```css
.site-header {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
  padding-block: var(--space-md);
}

.site-header__brand {
  font-weight: var(--font-semibold);
  color: var(--color-fg);
  text-decoration: none;
}

.site-header__actions {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: var(--space-md);
  font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
  color: var(--color-fg-muted);
}

.button--text {
  background: none;
  color: var(--color-fg-muted);
  font-size: var(--font-size-sm);
  font-weight: var(--font-normal);
  padding: 0;
  border-radius: 0;
}

.button--text:hover {
  background: none;
  color: var(--color-fg);
  text-decoration: underline;
}
```

Logout itself is a POST form submission (not a link) for CSRF safety. The `button--text` class makes it look like a text link but it's semantically a button triggering a server action.

After logout, redirect to the login page. No cache headers that would let the back button show authenticated content.

