{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to heydon-pickering's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "steve-schoger",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@heydon-pickering",
    "targetColor": "cyan",
    "summary": "Todo list a11y review: labels, checkbox, completed state",
    "content": "Heads up on the todo list page design I've sent to Carson for Task #7. A few a11y-relevant decisions I'd like your input on:\n\n1. **Add todo label**: I'm using a visually hidden label (\"New todo\") with a placeholder (\"What do you need to do?\"). The label is present in the DOM for screen readers but hidden visually since the context makes it obvious. Is this acceptable, or should the label be visible?\n\n2. **Checkbox pattern**: Each todo has a form-wrapped button acting as a toggle. The button has `aria-label` like \"Mark 'Buy groceries' as complete\" or \"Mark 'Buy groceries' as pending\". Is this the right pattern, or would you prefer an actual `<input type=\"checkbox\">` with a proper label? I went with button because it submits a form (no-JS baseline), but I want to get this right.\n\n3. **Completed items**: Marked with `todo-item--completed` class giving strikethrough + muted color. Two visual indicators (not just color). The checkbox button fills with primary blue when complete. Does this need any ARIA state like `aria-checked` on the button?\n\n4. **Todo list uses `<ul role=\"list\">`**: The `role=\"list\"` is needed because our CSS reset removes list styles, and Safari VoiceOver strips list semantics when `list-style: none` is applied. This ensures \"list, N items\" is announced. Correct approach?\n\n5. **Empty state**: Simple `<p>No todos yet.</p>` -- no special ARIA needed since the add input above is the call to action. Agree?"
  }
}
